# Prior work

List of related papers with one-paragraph summaries. Collected at the start of a new
project (5-10 papers) and extended whenever a new hypothesis is added.

## Format

```markdown
## [Author (Year)] Title

- **venue**: [journal / conference / arxiv id]
- **citations**: [Google Scholar / Semantic Scholar count]
- **URL / DOI**: [link]
- **main claim**: [one or two sentences]
- **method**:
  - model type: [math / classical ML / deep learning / RL / foundation model]
  - data: [universe, period, frequency]
  - validation: [split, k-fold, holdout, replication design, ...]
- **results**:
  - main metric: [primary metric value, confidence interval, effect size, etc.]
- **limitations** (stated by the authors, or evident weaknesses):
  - ...
- **relation to this research**: [use / compare / differentiate from / refute]
```

## Example

```markdown
## Smith et al. (2021) Benchmarking measurement reliability across sites

- **venue**: Journal of Applied Measurement 12(3): 101-120
- **citations**: 250+
- **URL**: https://example.org/example-paper
- **main claim**:
  A hierarchical measurement model improves calibration across heterogeneous
  sites compared with a pooled baseline.
- **method**:
  - model type: statistical model with ablation
  - data: public benchmark datasets, 2016-2020, monthly batches
  - validation: train/validation/test split plus held-out-site replication
- **results**:
  - Calibration error improved from 0.18 to 0.09 on held-out sites
  - Primary replication metric was stable across four cohorts
- **limitations**:
  - limited coverage of low-resource sites
  - missing long-horizon drift analysis
  - manual labeling protocol may not transfer to every domain
- **relation to this research**:
  Comparison reference. The differentiation is in the target population and
  replication design.
```

## Search strategy

- arxiv.org (topic-specific categories)
- SSRN (working papers and recent activity)
- Google Scholar — sort by citation count on the topic's base terms
- Snowball back from recent papers' references to canonical works

## When to update

Whenever a new hypothesis is added, revisit this file and add new papers if needed.
